Красивые, разноцветные "ёлочки" на поверхности некоторых кораллов, на самом деле являются щупальцами многощетинковых червей (Spirobranchus giganteus). Эти щупальца предназаначены для фильтрации воды и выделения из неё планктонных организмов, для питания червя.Коралловая колония находится в симбиозе с червями и получает дополнительную пищу от тока воды создающегося от движения ресничек на щупальцах животного.

Beautiful, colorful "fir-trees" on the surface of some corals, in fact, are the tentacles of polychaete worms(Spirobranchus giganteus). These tentacles are designed to filter water and isolate plankton organisms from it, to feed the worm. Coral colony is in symbiosis with worms and receives additional food from the current of water created from the movement of cilia on the tentacles of the animal.

An Orca attacks a Southern Sea Lion pup on the beach in Punta Norte, Argentina. Many dolphins have developed special feeding strategies to catch prey; techniques that evolve to suite the unique locations in which these animals live. The family of the orca pictured here, living off the coast of Patagonia, has developed a feeding strategy that includes beaching as a means of grabbing sea lion pups from the surf. The orca’s timing must be perfect, and these creatures must carefully select the location in which they will attack. 
Photographed on assignment for @NatGeo Magazine.

Praying Mantis
•
Moths, crickets, grasshoppers, flies, and other insects are usually the unfortunate recipients of unwanted mantid attention. However, the insects will also eat others of their own kind. The most famous example of this is the notorious mating behavior of the adult female, who sometimes eats her mate just after—or even during—mating. Yet this behavior seems not to deter males from reproduction.
